We will consider a Neural Network as a modular architecture, all layer and loss being a Module. We define the Linear, ReLU layers, necessary to implement a MLP, as well as a simple 2-layer MLP and the meaned square error function, MSE.

Q1.a. Read carefully the code below, and summarize in a few sentences what is the structure and the purpose of each class.

Module : Abstract class that defines the general structure of every layer(module). It specifies two abstract methods :

A forward : computes the output of the module
A backward : computes the gradient and the loss with respect to the modules inputs.

It serves as a parent class for all other components

MSE : Implements the Mean Squared Error loss between predictions and one-hot encoded target labels.

  make_target : Builds a one hot encoded target matrix of shape (batch_size, num_classes)
  forward : computes the average square difference between predictions and targets
  backward : computes and returns the gradient of the loss with respect to the model's outputs

Linear : A fully connected (dense) layer computing : $ y = xW^T + b $

  initialization : creates random weights and zero bias
  forward : computes the linear transformation of the input
  backward : computes gradient with respect to inputs, weights, and biases
  gradientStep : updates weights and biases, by doing a gradient descent with learning rate (1r)

ReLU : Implements the Rectified Linear Unit activation function.

  forward : replaces all negative values in the input by zero
  backward : propagates the gradient only on positive inputs

SimpleMLP : A simple neural network (multi-layer perceptron) whith one hidden layer.

  architecture : Linear (in_dimension -> 64) -> RELU -> Linear (64 -> num_classes).
  forward : passes data through each layer sequentially fc1 -> RELU -> fc2
  backward : propagates gradients in reverse order  : fc2 -> RELU -> fc1
  gradient : updates weights and biases of fc1 and fc2
In[]:
class Module(object):
    def __init__(self):
        self.gradInput = None
        self.output = None

    def forward(self, *input):
        """
        Defines the computation performed at every call.
        Should be overriden by all subclasses.
        """
        raise NotImplementedError

    def backward(self, *input):
        """
        Defines the computation performed at every call.
        Should be overriden by all subclasses.
        """
        raise NotImplementedError


class MSE(Module):
    """
    This implementation of the mean squared loss assumes that the data comes as a 2-dimensional array
    of size (batch_size, num_classes) and the labels as a vector of size (batch_size)
    """
    def __init__(self, num_classes=10):
        super(MSE, self).__init__()
        self.num_classes = num_classes

    def make_target(self, x, labels):
        target = np.zeros([x.shape[0], self.num_classes])
        for i in range(x.shape[0]):
            target[i, labels[i]] = 1

        return target

    def forward(self, x, labels):
        target = self.make_target(x, labels)
        self.output = np.sum((target-x)**2, axis=1)
        return np.mean(self.output)

    def backward(self, x, labels):
        target = self.make_target(x, labels)
        self.gradInput = -2*(target - x) / x.shape[0]
        return self.gradInput


class Linear(Module):
    """
    The input is supposed to have two dimensions (batch_size, in_features)
    """
    def __init__(self, in_features, out_features, bias=True):
        super(Linear, self).__init__()
        self.in_features = in_features
        self.out_features = out_features

        std = math.sqrt(2/in_features) # He init because we have ReLU.
        self.weight = std*np.random.randn(out_features, in_features)
        self.bias = np.zeros(out_features)

    def forward(self, x):
        self.output = np.dot(x, self.weight.transpose()) + self.bias[None, :]
        return self.output

    def backward(self, x, gradOutput):
        self.gradInput = np.dot(gradOutput, self.weight)
        self.gradWeight = np.dot(gradOutput.transpose(), x)
        self.gradBias = np.sum(gradOutput, axis=0)
        return self.gradInput

    def gradientStep(self, lr):
        self.weight = self.weight - lr*self.gradWeight
        self.bias = self.bias - lr*self.gradBias


class ReLU(Module):
    def __init__(self, bias=True):
        super(ReLU, self).__init__()

    def forward(self, x):
        self.output = x.clip(0)
        return self.output

    def backward(self, x, gradOutput):
        self.gradInput = (x>0) * gradOutput
        return self.gradInput


class SimpleMLP(Module):
    """
    This class is a simple example of a neural network, composed of two
    linear layers, with a ReLU non-linearity in the middle
    """
    def __init__(self, in_dimension=784, num_classes=10):
        super(SimpleMLP, self).__init__()
        self.fc1 = Linear(in_dimension, 64)
        self.relu1 = ReLU()
        self.fc2 = Linear(64, num_classes)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.fc1.forward(x)
        x = self.relu1.forward(x)
        x = self.fc2.forward(x)
        return x

    def backward(self, x, gradient):
        gradient = self.fc2.backward(self.relu1.output, gradient)
        gradient = self.relu1.backward(self.fc1.output, gradient)
        gradient = self.fc1.backward(x, gradient)
        return gradient

    def gradientStep(self, lr):
        self.fc2.gradientStep(lr)
        self.fc1.gradientStep(lr)

Q1.b. Read and understand the code above and explain in a few words why we need to split data in {train, val, test}

If we don't split data in {train, val, test} and only train the model on the entire dataset, the model will likely overfit and we wont be able to evaluate its real performance.

Splitting the data allows us to test the model, on unseen data. which gives a more reliable estimate of how it will perform on new data.

The train set is used to learn the parameters of the model

The validation test is used to monitor overfitting during training and tune hyperparameters.

The Test set is used only once, at the end, to evaluate the final model on a fully unseen dataset.

Q3.a. Write a function train_iter(model, loss, batch_data, batch_labels, lr) that performs one iteration of gradient descent given model and loss (subclasses of Module) on a batch (batch_data, batch_labels) with a learning rate lr, and returns the training loss value.

Help:

  1. Make the predictions (model.forward)
  2. Compute the loss between the predictions and the labels (loss.forward)
  3. Compute its gradient wrt the predictions and the labels (loss.backward)
  4. Backpropagate the gradient into the model (model.backward)
  5. Perform gradient descent (model.gradientStep)
In[]:
#We follow upper procedure for training :

def train_iter(model, loss, batch_data, batch_labels, lr):
    """ Performs one iteration of gradient descent on the model"""
    predictions = model.forward(batch_data)
    loss_value = loss.forward(predictions, batch_labels)
    gradient = loss.backward(predictions, batch_labels)
    model.backward(batch_data,gradient)
    model.gradientStep(lr)
    return loss_value

Q4.a. Write a function evaluate(model, loss, data, labels) that returns a couple (loss, accuracy) corresponding to the loss and accuracy computed on some data.

NB: for loops are so slow, avoid them as much as possible!

In[]:
def evaluate(model, loss, data, labels):
    """ Evaluate the model on the given data and labels
        Returns the couple (loss,accuracy)
    """
    predictions = model.forward(data)
    loss_value = loss.forward(predictions, labels)
    predictions = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1) # Convert to class predictions
    accuracy = np.mean(predictions == labels) # Expectation of correct predictions
    return loss_value, accuracy

Help:

  • plt.bar can be used to do a barplot
  • np.unique is useful to compute unique elements in an array as well as respective count
In[]:
predictions = model.forward(val_data)
predicted_labels = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)

error_rates = []

for i in range(10):
  mask = (val_labels == i)
  total = np.sum(mask)
  if total == 0:
      error_rates.append(0)
      continue
  errors = np.sum(predicted_labels[mask] != val_labels[mask])
  error_rate = 100 * errors / total
  error_rates.append(error_rate)

plt.figure(figsize=(7,4))
plt.bar(range(10), error_rates, color='green', edgecolor='black')
plt.xlabel('Class (Number)')
plt.ylabel('Error percentage (%)')
plt.title('Classification errors depending on classes')
plt.xticks(range(10))
plt.show()

wrong_idx = np.where(predicted_labels != val_labels)[0]

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
for i, idx in enumerate(np.random.choice(wrong_idx, 10, replace=False)):
    plt.subplot(2,5,i+1)
    plt.bar(range(10),predictions[idx])
    plt.title(f"True: {val_labels[idx]}, Pred: {predicted_labels[idx]}")
    plt.xticks(range(10))
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

We can see that the model makes a lot of errors when recognizing eights, and it also shows some confusion with digits 2, 5, 9 and 3. However, these digits may vary depending on the training process, because of the randomness of training. These differences in accuracy can be explained by the varying difficulty of recognizing some complex patterns that help distinguish digits (even more so with an MLP that has no spatial structure). A larger architecture could be able to capture more complex patterns and thus make fewer confusions. In most failure cases, the correct class often appears as the second highest value in the prediction vector, showing that the model is quite close to the right prediction.

Part Ib. Training a neural network

Q5.a. Write a train_epoch(model, loss, data, labels, val_data, val_labels, lr, batch_size) function that trains a model for a whole epoch and returns train and val losses as well as accuracies on validation every 10 iterations (do not print anything during trainin this time). Test it to train a SimpleMLP from scratch for 2 epochs with the same parameters as in question 3.b.

In[]:
def train_epoch(model, loss, data, labels, val_data, val_labels, lr, batch_size):
    train_losses = []
    val_losses = []
    val_accuracies = []

    indices = np.arange(len(data))
    np.random.shuffle(indices)
    data = data[indices]
    labels = labels[indices]

    for i in range(len(data) // batch_size):
        batch_data = data[i * batch_size:(i + 1) * batch_size] #Take the batch data
        batch_labels = labels[i * batch_size:(i + 1) * batch_size]

        loss_value = train_iter(model, loss, batch_data, batch_labels, lr) #Train the model on the batch

        # Evaluation every 10 batches
        if i % 10 == 0:
            val_loss, val_accuracy = evaluate(model, loss, val_data, val_labels)
            train_losses.append(loss_value)
            val_losses.append(val_loss)
            val_accuracies.append(val_accuracy)

    return train_losses, val_losses, val_accuracies

lr = 1e-2
batch_size = 16
model = SimpleMLP()
loss = MSE()

train_losses_1, val_losses_1, val_accuracies_1 = train_epoch(model, loss, train_data, train_labels, val_data, val_labels, lr, batch_size)
train_losses_2, val_losses_2, val_accuracies_2 = train_epoch(model, loss, train_data, train_labels, val_data, val_labels, lr, batch_size)

train_losses = train_losses_1 + train_losses_2 # Concatenate the losses from both epochs
val_losses = val_losses_1 + val_losses_2 # Concatenate the losses from both epochs
val_accuracies = val_accuracies_1 + val_accuracies_2 # Concatenate the accuracies from both epochs

Q6.a. Based on the previous questions, design a function

train(model, loss, train_data, train_labels, val_data, val_labels, ...)

that performs a full training of the input model on the training data. Choose the arguments of your function (for instance, batch_size, lr, epochs, etc) according to what seems relevant to you. This function should plot at the end the evolution of train / val losses and accuracies.

In[]:
def train(model, loss, train_data, train_labels, val_data, val_labels, lr, batch_size, epochs):
  train_losses = []
  val_losses = []
  val_accuracies = []
  for epoch in range(epochs):
    train_epoch_losses, val_epoch_losses, val_epoch_accuracies = train_epoch(model, loss, train_data, train_labels, val_data, val_labels, lr, batch_size)
    train_losses.extend(train_epoch_losses)
    val_losses.extend(val_epoch_losses)
    val_accuracies.extend(val_epoch_accuracies)

  plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
  plt.plot(range(len(train_losses)),train_losses,color ='green', label='Train loss')
  plt.plot(range(len(val_losses)),val_losses, color = 'orange', label='Val loss')
  plt.xlabel('Iteration number')
  plt.ylabel('Loss')
  plt.title('Loss throught iterations')
  plt.legend()
  plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)
  plt.show()

  plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
  plt.plot(range(len(val_accuracies)),val_accuracies,color = 'orange', label='Val accuracy')
  plt.xlabel('Iteration number')
  plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
  plt.title('Accuracy throught iterations')
  plt.legend()
  plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)
  plt.show()

  print('Final results after training:')
  print(f'Final train loss: {train_losses[-1]:.3f}, final val loss: {val_losses[-1]:.3f}')
  print(f'final val accuracy: {val_accuracies[-1]:.3f}')

  return train_losses, val_losses, val_accuracies

Part II. Overfitting

Q7. What's the number of parameters in the network SimpleMLP used in the first section?

The first layer has dimensions 784 -> 64. Including the bias, it has 784 64 + 64 = 50,240 parameters.

The second layer has dimensions 64 -> 10. Including the bias, it has 64 10 + 10 = 650 parameters.

Thus, the total number of parameters in the SimpleMLP network from the first section is 50,240 + 650 = 50,890.

Q8.a. Rewrite the definition of SimpleMLP to allow changing the dimension of the hidden layer. Test it by training 1 epoch with 128 hidden features and plotting its performances.

In[]:
class SimpleMLP(Module):
    """
    This class is a simple example of a neural network, composed of two
    linear layers, with a ReLU non-linearity in the middle
    """
    def __init__(self,hidden_feature=64, in_dimension=784, num_classes=10):
        super(SimpleMLP, self).__init__()
        self.fc1 = Linear(in_dimension, hidden_feature)
        self.relu1 = ReLU()
        self.fc2 = Linear(hidden_feature, num_classes)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.fc1.forward(x)
        x = self.relu1.forward(x)
        x = self.fc2.forward(x)
        return x

    def backward(self, x, gradient):
        gradient = self.fc2.backward(self.relu1.output, gradient)
        gradient = self.relu1.backward(self.fc1.output, gradient)
        gradient = self.fc1.backward(x, gradient)
        return gradient

    def gradientStep(self, lr):
        self.fc2.gradientStep(lr)
        self.fc1.gradientStep(lr)


model = SimpleMLP(128)
loss = MSE()
lr = 1e-2
batch_size = 16
epochs = 1
train_losses, val_losses, val_accuracies = train(model, loss, train_data, train_labels, val_data, val_labels, lr, batch_size, epochs)

Q8.b. Define a class DoubleMLP with three Linear layers and parameters to change their dimensions. Test it by training 1 epoch with [64, 32] hidden features and plotting its performances. Does it look better than SimpleMLPso far?

In[]:
class DoubleMLP(Module):
    """
    This class is a simple example of a neural network, composed of three
    linear layers, with a ReLU non-linearity in the middle
    """
    def __init__(self, hidden_feature_1=64, hidden_feature_2=64, in_dimension=784, num_classes=10):
        super(DoubleMLP, self).__init__()
        self.fc1 = Linear(in_dimension, hidden_feature_1)
        self.relu1 = ReLU()
        self.fc2 = Linear(hidden_feature_1, hidden_feature_2)
        self.relu2 = ReLU()
        self.fc3 = Linear(hidden_feature_2, num_classes)


    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.fc1.forward(x)
        x = self.relu1.forward(x)
        x = self.fc2.forward(x)
        x = self.relu2.forward(x)
        x = self.fc3.forward(x)
        return x

    def backward(self, x, gradient):
        gradient = self.fc3.backward(self.relu2.output, gradient)
        gradient = self.relu2.backward(self.fc2.output, gradient)
        gradient = self.fc2.backward(self.relu1.output, gradient)
        gradient = self.relu1.backward(self.fc1.output, gradient)
        gradient = self.fc1.backward(x, gradient)
        return gradient

    def gradientStep(self, lr):
        self.fc3.gradientStep(lr)
        self.fc2.gradientStep(lr)
        self.fc1.gradientStep(lr)

batch_size = 16

  • DeepMLP([64, 64, 64]) should be a MLP with four linear layers...

class DeepMLP (Module):
    """
    This class is a simple example of a neural network, composed of
    linear layers, with a ReLU non-linearity
    """
    def __init__(self, hidden_features, in_dimension=784, num_classes=10):
        super(DeepMLP, self).__init__()
        self.layers = [] # Layers are now listed in a list
        self.activations = [] # Activations are now listed in a list

        prev_dim = in_dimension # Parameter to ensure right dimensions for the layers
        for h in hidden_features:
            self.layers.append(Linear(prev_dim, h))
            self.activations.append(ReLU())
            prev_dim = h

        self.layers.append(Linear(prev_dim, num_classes))

    def forward(self, x):
            self.inputs = [x]
            for i in range(len(self.layers)): # Iteration over layers
                x = self.layers[i].forward(x)
                if i < len(self.activations):
                    x = self.activations[i].forward(x)
                self.inputs.append(x)
            return x

    def backward(self, x, gradient):
        for i in range(len(self.layers) - 1, -1, -1): # Iteration over layers in reverse order
            if i < len(self.activations):
                gradient = self.activations[i].backward(self.layers[i].output, gradient)
            gradient = self.layers[i].backward(
                self.inputs[i], gradient
            )
        return gradient

    def gradientStep(self, lr): # Iteration of gradient step over all layers
        for i in range(len(self.layers)):
            self.layers[i].gradientStep(lr)

Analysis of hyperparameters :

We experimented with various hyperparameter configurations, analyzed them, and tried to explain their impact on model accuracy.

Testing different configurations suggests that the model performs better with large dimensions in the first layers, which capture the 784 inputs more effectively. However, smaller sizes in the last layer are more efficient. To recognize different digits, we can expect that the last layer of our model captures large patterns in the drawing and associates them with specific numbers. As shown in this lecture video (https://www.3blue1brown.com/lessons/gradient-descent), this hypothesis is not entirely realisticespecially for an MLP, which does not capture spatial patternsand the real behavior of the system seems non-intuitive to humans. However, even if the patterns recognized by the model are not interpretable by humans, the hypothesis that only a limited number of such patterns (and therefore fewer neurons in the last layer) are needed seems relevant. Besides, using more layer increases a lot the computational cost whithout improving the accuracy.

lr: The learning rate affects a lot the efficiency of the model. A too low learning rate (around 1e-3) slow down convergence, whereas a large lr (greater than 1e-1) causes the loss to diverge. Thus, by testing different values, an lr as high as possible (without divergence) is optimal. We can see that this observation follows the advice in lecture 1:

The most common strategy is to pick a high learning rate that still leads to steady loss decrease and keep it constant until convergence (handout p.18).

This enables the model to escape local minima during training. The next step, explained in the lecture, would be to train the model again with a lower lr to converge to a more precise minimum. Thus, we can expect better results with a controlled learning rate during training. Althought, here, in practice a second training doesn't improve results a lot.

batch_size: The batch size controls the level of stochasticity during training and is limited by the dataset size. A small batch size greatly increases the computational cost of the training since each epoch takes more iterations. However, larger batch sizes require more epochs to reach same accurracies. In the lecture, it is recommended to use large batch sizes (while still much smaller than the dataset size). In practice batch_size around 100 tends to give better results

epochs: Epochs really depend on the other hyperparameter values, but in practice, more epochs enable the model to fully converge. However, too many epochs lead to overfitting, which can be observed by the gap between training and validation loss. To obtain better results, the number of epochs should be tuned to enable convergence without too much overfitting.

# We first modify the DeepMLP class to use it with different non-linearities

class DeepMLP (Module):
    """
    This class is a simple example of a neural network, composed of
    linear layers, with a non-linearity function
    """
    def __init__(self, hidden_features,non_linearity_function=ReLU, in_dimension=784, num_classes=10): # We add a parameter to choose the non-linearity function
        super(DeepMLP, self).__init__()
        self.layers = []
        self.activations = []
        self.non_linearity_function = non_linearity_function

        prev_dim = in_dimension
        for h in hidden_features:
            self.layers.append(Linear(prev_dim, h))
            self.activations.append(self.non_linearity_function()) # We can now use any non-linearity function here
            prev_dim = h

        self.layers.append(Linear(prev_dim, num_classes))

    def forward(self, x):
            self.inputs = [x]
            for i in range(len(self.layers)):
                x = self.layers[i].forward(x)
                if i < len(self.activations):
                    x = self.activations[i].forward(x)
                self.inputs.append(x)
            return x

    def backward(self, x, gradient):
        for i in range(len(self.layers) - 1, -1, -1):
            if i < len(self.activations):
                gradient = self.activations[i].backward(self.layers[i].output, gradient)
            gradient = self.layers[i].backward(
                self.inputs[i], gradient
            )
        return gradient

    def gradientStep(self, lr):
        for i in range(len(self.layers)):
            self.layers[i].gradientStep(lr)

#Then we can define other non-linearities class

class Sigmoid(Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(Sigmoid, self).__init__()

    def forward(self, x):
        self.output = 1 / (1 + np.exp(-x)) # Sigmoid function
        return self.output

    def backward(self, x, gradOutput):
        self.gradInput = gradOutput * (self.output * (1 - self.output)) # Derivative of the sigmoid function : f'(x) = f(x)(1-f(x))
        return self.gradInput

class Tanh(Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(Tanh, self).__init__()

    def forward(self, x):
        self.output = np.tanh(x) # Tanh function
        return self.output

    def backward(self, x, gradOutput):
        self.gradInput = gradOutput * (1 - self.output**2) # Derivative of the tanh function : f'(x) = 1 - f(x)^2
        return self.gradInput

class LeakyReLU(Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(LeakyReLU, self).__init__()

    def forward(self, x):
        self.output = np.where(x > 0, x, 0.01 * x) # LeakyReLU function
        return self.output

    def backward(self, x, gradOutput):
        self.gradInput = gradOutput * np.where(x > 0, 1, 0.01) # Derivative of LeakyReLU function
        return self.gradInput

Q11. Implement and test different loss functions (L1, Cross-Entropy)

In[]:
# We define other loss functions class

class L1(Module):
    """
    This implementation of the L1 loss assumes that the data comes as a 2-dimensional array
    of size (batch_size, num_classes) and the labels as a vector of size (batch_size)
    """
    def __init__(self, num_classes=10):
        super(L1, self).__init__()
        self.num_classes = num_classes

    def make_target(self, x, labels):
        target = np.zeros([x.shape[0], self.num_classes])
        for i in range(x.shape[0]):
            target[i, labels[i]] = 1

        return target

    def forward(self, x, labels):
        target = self.make_target(x, labels)
        self.output = np.sum(np.abs(target-x), axis=1)
        return np.mean(self.output)

    def backward(self, x, labels):
        target = self.make_target(x, labels)
        self.gradInput = np.sign(x - target) / x.shape[0]
        return self.gradInput

class Cross_Entropy(Module):
    """
    This implementation of the Cross_Entropy loss assumes that the data comes as a 2-dimensional array
    of size (batch_size, num_classes) and the labels as a vector of size (batch_size)
    """
    def __init__(self, num_classes=10):
        super(Cross_Entropy, self).__init__()
        self.num_classes = num_classes

    def make_target(self, x, labels):
        target = np.zeros([x.shape[0], self.num_classes])
        for i in range(x.shape[0]):
            target[i, labels[i]] = 1
        return target

    def softmax(self, x): # Softmax function to convert logits to probabilities
        exp_x = np.exp(x - np.max(x, axis=1, keepdims=True))
        return exp_x / np.sum(exp_x, axis=1, keepdims=True)

    def forward(self, x, labels):
        probs = self.softmax(x)
        target = self.make_target(x, labels)
        self.output = -np.sum(target * np.log(probs + 1e-9), axis=1) # We add a small value to avoid log(0)
        return np.mean(self.output)

    def backward(self, x, labels):
        probs = self.softmax(x)
        target = self.make_target(x, labels)
        self.gradInput = (probs - target) / x.shape[0]
        return self.gradInput

The L1 loss gives very poor results, which can be explained by the fact that its derivative can only take the value +-1. As a result, it is very difficult to converge to any minimum because it cannot adapt the step size. In practice a good loss should produce smaller gradient near a minimum, and on the contrary, produce bigger steps when it is far from any optimal solution.

The Cross-Entropy Loss is more effective. It uses the Softmax function to normalize the predictions under the form of a probability distribution over the classes. To implement this loss (and especially the Softmax normalization), I used online ressources on internet, mostly this kaggle tutorial : https://www.kaggle.com/code/dhadheechi/mnist-using-fast-ai-and-cross-entropy-function.
This loss, penalizes a lot confident but wrong predictions, which usualy leads to better results on classification problems. However,here, the results obtained with Cross-Entropy are slightly worse than those with MSE(). We can also observe from the loss evolution that the convergence with this loss is faster

Q12. Add some momentum to your training procedure. How does it change the training behavior?

In[]:
# We modify the Linear class to add momentum in gradient step

class Linear(Module):
    """
    Fully-connected (dense) layer with momentum-based gradient updates.
    Input shape:  (batch_size, in_features)
    Output shape: (batch_size, out_features)
    """
    def __init__(self, in_features, out_features, bias=True):
        super(Linear, self).__init__()
        self.in_features = in_features
        self.out_features = out_features

        std = math.sqrt(2 / in_features)
        self.weight = std * np.random.randn(out_features, in_features)
        self.bias = np.zeros(out_features)

        self.delta_w = np.zeros_like(self.weight) # Momentum term for weights
        self.delta_b = np.zeros_like(self.bias) # Momentum term for biases

    def forward(self, x):
        """
        Compute the forward pass: output = x * W^T + b
        """
        self.output = np.dot(x, self.weight.T) + self.bias[None, :]
        return self.output

    def backward(self, x, gradOutput):
        """
        Compute gradients for backpropagation.
        """
        self.gradInput = np.dot(gradOutput, self.weight)
        self.gradWeight = np.dot(gradOutput.T, x)
        self.gradBias = np.sum(gradOutput, axis=0)
        return self.gradInput

    def gradientStep(self, lr, momentum=0.8):  # Added momentum parameter
        """
        Gradient update with momentum:
        """
        self.delta_w = momentum * self.delta_w + (1 - momentum) * self.gradWeight # Update momentum term for weights
        self.delta_b = momentum * self.delta_b + (1 - momentum) * self.gradBias # Update momentum term for biases

        self.weight -= lr * self.delta_w
        self.bias   -= lr * self.delta_b


#Most of previous functions need to be modified to include momentum

# We modify the training functions to include momentum

def train_iter(model, loss, batch_data, batch_labels, lr, momentum): # Added momentum parameter
    """Performs one training iteration on a batch."""
    predictions = model.forward(batch_data)
    loss_value = loss.forward(predictions, batch_labels)
    gradient = loss.backward(predictions, batch_labels)
    model.backward(batch_data, gradient)
    model.gradientStep(lr, momentum) # Added momentum parameter
    return loss_value


def train_epoch(model, loss, data, labels, val_data, val_labels, lr, momentum, batch_size): # Added momentum parameter
    """Trains the model for one epoch and evaluates every 10 iterations."""
    train_losses = []
    val_losses = []
    val_accuracies = []

    indices = np.arange(len(data))
    np.random.shuffle(indices)
    data = data[indices]
    labels = labels[indices]

    for i in range(len(data) // batch_size):
        batch_data = data[i * batch_size:(i + 1) * batch_size]
        batch_labels = labels[i * batch_size:(i + 1) * batch_size]

        loss_value = train_iter(model, loss, batch_data, batch_labels, lr, momentum) # Added momentum parameter

        if i % 10 == 0:
            val_loss, val_accuracy = evaluate(model, loss, val_data, val_labels)

            train_losses.append(loss_value)
            val_losses.append(val_loss)
            val_accuracies.append(val_accuracy)

    return train_losses, val_losses, val_accuracies


def train(model, loss, train_data, train_labels, val_data, val_labels, lr, momentum, batch_size, epochs): # Added momentum parameter
    """Trains the model for multiple epochs and plots the results."""
    train_losses = []
    val_losses = []
    val_accuracies = []

    for epoch in range(epochs):
        train_epoch_losses, val_epoch_losses, val_epoch_accuracies = train_epoch(
            model, loss, train_data, train_labels, val_data, val_labels, lr, momentum, batch_size # Added momentum parameter
        )
        train_losses.extend(train_epoch_losses)
        val_losses.extend(val_epoch_losses)
        val_accuracies.extend(val_epoch_accuracies)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    plt.plot(range(len(train_losses)), train_losses, label='Train loss')
    plt.plot(range(len(val_losses)), val_losses, label='Val loss')
    plt.xlabel('Iteration number')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.title('Loss through iterations')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)
    plt.show()

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    plt.plot(range(len(val_accuracies)), val_accuracies,color ='orange', label='Val accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Iteration number')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.title('Accuracy through iterations')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)
    plt.show()

    print('Final results after training:')
    print(f'Final train loss: {train_losses[-1]:.3f}, final val loss: {val_losses[-1]:.3f}')
    print(f'Final val accuracy: {val_accuracies[-1]:.3f}')

    return train_losses, val_losses, val_accuracies

Momentum is very promising for improving our results. It encourages coherent updates in the same direction, which helps the optimization process avoid getting stuck in local minima. Moreover, it smooths out oscillations during training, allowing faster and more stable convergence. This feature introduce a new hyperparameter, after trying some different values, it appears that a momentum around 0.7 gives the best results.
